{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657497","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657497"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:30:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:30:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20536"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20536","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20536"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.43,0.13,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13415"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92983"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13415","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13415"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20536"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"11723"},{"type":"tags","id":"12477"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"31910"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36095"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92983"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA microscopic examination of a kidney biopsy specimen obtained from a patient with diabetes mellitus with declining renal function is reviewed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following microscopic findings is most likely to be seen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Concentric smooth muscle proliferation","Homogeneous eosinophilic thickening","Fibrinoid necrosis","Granulomatous inflammation","Thrombotic occlusion"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EHyaline arteriolosclerosis is a degenerative condition primarily affecting small arterioles, commonly seen in patients with chronic hypertension and diabetes mellitus. It occurs due to the deposition of plasma proteins that have leaked through damaged endothelium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHomogeneous eosinophilic thickening\u003C/strong\u003E of the vessel wall is the classic microscopic finding in hyaline arteriolosclerosis. This appears as a pink, glassy material on haematoxylin and eosin staining and represents the accumulation of plasma proteins and basement membrane material.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConcentric smooth muscle proliferation\u003C/strong\u003E is characteristic of hyperplastic arteriolosclerosis, which is seen in more severe or malignant hypertension rather than chronic, benign hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrinoid necrosis\u003C/strong\u003E is typically seen in malignant hypertension or vasculitis, representing acute vascular injury rather than chronic changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGranulomatous inflammation\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest vasculitis such as granulomatosis with polyangiitis, which is a different pathological process entirely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombotic occlusion\u003C/strong\u003E would be seen in conditions such as thrombotic microangiopathy or antiphospholipid syndrome, rather than the chronic vascular changes of hyaline arteriolosclerosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHyaline arteriolosclerosis is a common finding in elderly patients and those with diabetes or hypertension. It represents a degenerative process that can lead to reduced organ perfusion over time, particularly affecting the kidneys and retina.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hyaline arteriolosclerosis is characterised by homogeneous pink deposits in arteriolar walls","Hyaline arteriolosclerosis is commonly associated with hypertension and diabetes mellitus","Hyaline arteriolosclerosis primarily affects small arterioles"],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 493-494"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20536"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76336"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T12:11:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T12:12:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13415"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92983"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"he